x4freetext: Experiment was performed at the
flight path 14 at the Manuel Lujan, Jr., Neutron
Scattering Center at the Los Alamos Neutron Science
Center
Vacuum-pressed enriched
rhenium metal powder with weight of 987.1 mg and
thickness of 1mm was encapsulated in a disk-shaped
polycarbonate target holder.
Experiment performed using GEANIE array,
configured with eight planar and 10 coaxial high-purity
germanium detectors. Each detector was Compton
suppressed using a bismuth germanate (BGO) shield. Of
the 18 installed detectors, seven of each type
provided usable data for offline analysis.
The proton beam has a macropulse repetition
rate of 40 or 100 Hz, with each 625 mu-s macropulse
further divided into numerous subnanosecond
micropulses spaced 1.8 mu-s apart. The pulsed nature
of the beam provides the ability to measure neutron
energies using the time-of-flight method, and the
detection system is capable of resolving neutron
energies from 0.6 to 200 MeV
Spallation neutrons with energies ranging
from 100 keV to 600 MeV are produced by directing
pulses of H- ions with an average current of 0.5 to 4
mu-A at a natural W target
